        analysis:
          'The question of whether the clones possess souls is central to the novel and drives much of its emotional power. Ishiguro uses the Hailsham art programme as a vehicle for exploring this theme: Madame collects the students\' artwork because the guardians hope to prove that clones have souls and deserve humane treatment. The irony is that the students themselves are largely unaware of why their creativity matters so much to the outside world. Kathy\'s reflective, deeply human narration itself serves as the strongest argument that the clones are fully conscious beings with rich inner lives. The novel forces readers to confront uncomfortable questions about what constitutes personhood. The clones love, grieve, feel jealousy and hope, yet society treats them as disposable organ farms. Ishiguro draws a deliberate parallel with real-world dehumanisation: when a society benefits from the exploitation of a group, it finds ways to deny that group\'s humanity. The Gallery, the rumour of deferrals, and the students\' desperate search for their "possibles" all reflect a yearning to be recognised as real people rather than copies. Ultimately the novel suggests that the soul is demonstrated not through any external proof but through the capacity to feel, remember, and narrate one\'s own life.'
