          'Othello is the play\'s tragic protagonist: a Moorish general in the Venetian army, respected for his military prowess but never fully accepted in the racist society he serves. Shakespeare initially presents him as a figure of immense dignity and self-possession. His speech before the Senate — recounting how he won Desdemona\'s love through his stories of adventure — reveals both his rhetorical power and his vulnerability: he is a man who defines himself through narrative and performance, and when his story is poisoned by Iago, his identity disintegrates. Othello\'s tragic flaw is not jealousy per se but the insecurity that makes jealousy possible. As a Black outsider in Venice, he is acutely aware that his marriage to Desdemona transgresses social norms, and this awareness makes him susceptible to Iago\'s suggestion that Desdemona\'s love is itself unnatural. His descent from noble composure to incoherent rage is one of Shakespeare\'s most devastating character arcs. His language deteriorates from eloquent verse to fragmented, animalistic prose as jealousy takes hold, mirroring the destruction of his rationality and selfhood. His final speech — "one that loved not wisely but too well" — attempts to reclaim his narrative dignity, but critics debate whether this represents genuine self-knowledge or a final act of self-mythologising.',
